window.COURSE_DATA = {"language":"en","lastDownload":"2022-12-02T16:34:27-05:00","title":"Product Design Prework V2","modules":[{"id":44910,"name":"Introduction","status":"completed","unlockDate":null,"prereqs":[],"requirement":"all","sequential":true,"exportId":"g7fce43fff7d15bd1e920857893df42f4","items":[{"id":433522,"title":"Welcome!","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003ch4\u003eWelcome to Flatiron School! We're thrilled that you've joined our community of learners!\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe following content is designed for passionate, curious, self-driven, and serious about learning. We are comrades in a never-ending quest for knowledge. While there are no shortcuts, we believe that you will learn quickly by providing knowledge in an optimized order, reinforcing knowledge with hands-on, feedback-driven practice, and providing space for discussion.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOur goal is to provide the right materials, support, and structure \u003cem\u003eyou\u003c/em\u003e need to discover your own love for designing outstanding products.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePre-work is required to start at Flatiron School\u003c/strong\u003e and you have access to this useful material even prior to applying. Please note some resources mentioned throughout are only available to enrolled students, such as community and technical coach support.\u0026nbsp;\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIf youâ€™re just researching the programs, keep in mind that this is the same pre-course work admitted students are working through. Some of this information will seem granular, just work through as much as you can and know that you will have time to revisit content should you go through our admissions process. \u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch4\u003eThe Flatiron Community\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWe don't believe in learning alone. As you make progress, expect to bump into other learners just like you, ready and willing to help each other succeed. Together, we can go further than we could ever go alone. We expect everyone here to be friendly, respectful, helpful, and nice.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"welcome"},{"id":433523,"title":"Introduction to Canvas","type":"ContextModuleSubHeader","indent":0,"locked":false},{"id":433524,"title":"What is Canvas?","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003eCanvas is a learning platform used by universities and educational institutions across the country and the world. Flatiron School uses Canvas to deliver all curriculum content for your program.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCanvas is where all official Flatiron School communication, assignment submission, grading, attendance, etc., will take place for the entirety of your course. You should check Canvas multiple times a day for updates, announcements, assignments, and the day's schedule. Canvas hosts many features that you will become familiar with over your time with Flatiron School. The following lessons will introduce you to and explain some of these most important functions. You can also download the Canvas app from the App Store.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"what-is-canvas"},{"id":433525,"title":"Navigating Canvas","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/PVfkFD45hL0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDashboard\u003c/strong\u003e - the first thing you see when you log into Canvas, the Dashboard gives a high level view of the courses in which you're enrolled. Your instructor will release new courses as you go through the program.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGlobal Navigation\u003c/strong\u003e - static menu on the left side of the page and accessible from any page on Canvas, the Global Navigation gives you direct access to your courses and other information in Canvas.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSidebar\u003c/strong\u003e - found within each course, the Sidebar houses various features that allow access to the course materials.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eView the video tutorial for more information on how to use Canvas effectively.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"navigating-canvas"},{"id":433526,"title":"Lesson Types in Canvas","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003ch2\u003eCOURSES\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYour Flatiron School program is broken up into courses. Each course represents a section of our core curriculum. The Flatiron School course structure is something that we'll discuss in more detail in later lessons. For now, we'll discuss the content types you are likely to see in the Canvas platform.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eMODULES\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFlatiron School organizes content within courses by breaking them up into modules. The modules will control the entire course flow, and within them, you'll find all your lessons, labs, assignments, and quizzes for the course. Modules can hold several types of content:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePage:\u003c/strong\u003e a page of content to read\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDiscussion:\u003c/strong\u003e a course discussion in which teachers and students can actively participate\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eQuiz:\u003c/strong\u003e A course quiz, generally multiple choice questions or true/false questions\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAssignment:\u003c/strong\u003e A course assignment. Assignments are graded projects that count toward your final score\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLink or External Tool:\u003c/strong\u003e an external link or tool to view information outside of the course\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFile:\u003c/strong\u003e a file to download or view\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou may be required to perform certain actions to complete a module. Requirements may include:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eView:\u003c/strong\u003e You must view the item.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMark as done:\u003c/strong\u003e You must mark the module item as done before progressing to the next item.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eContribute:\u003c/strong\u003e You must post a reply to the discussion topic or contribute content to a page.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSubmit:\u003c/strong\u003e You must submit the assignment, graded discussion, or quiz.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eScore at least X points:\u003c/strong\u003e You must submit the assignment with a minimum of the shown score.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou can find the 'Modules' button on the sidebar on the left-hand side within each course.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eASSIGNMENTS\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhile the module controls the flow of the entire course, you can also access a running list of your course assignments via the 'Assignments' button on your Sidebar on the left-hand side within the course.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBy default, assignments are grouped by overdue assignments, upcoming assignments, undated assignments, and past assignments.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eEach assignment includes an icon designating an assignment, discussion, or quiz and will also display availability dates, due dates, and the number of points the assignment is worth.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou can find the 'Assignments' button on the sidebar on the left-hand side within each course.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"lesson-types-in-canvas"},{"id":433527,"title":"Course Structure","type":"ContextModuleSubHeader","indent":0,"locked":false},{"id":433528,"title":"Product Design Program Overview","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/A4c4uSOE7Ic\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we discuss the overall course structure for the Product Design program and talk about all five phases of the program in detail.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"product-design-program-overview"}]},{"id":44911,"name":"Pre-assessment","status":"completed","unlockDate":null,"prereqs":[],"requirement":"all","sequential":false,"exportId":"gfbcbf373b622c042a82d0ddbfb4961d4","items":[{"id":433529,"title":"Prework: Pre Assessment","type":"Quizzes::Quiz","indent":0,"locked":false,"assignmentExportId":"gd41d8cd98f00b204e9800998ecf8427e","questionCount":10,"timeLimit":null,"attempts":3,"graded":true,"pointsPossible":10.0,"dueAt":null,"lockAt":null,"unlockAt":null,"requirement":"must_submit","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003eTake this assessment before you start the coursework. This quiz is intended to gauge your current understanding of Product Design topics before you start the prework. Do your best to answer the questions, but know that this assignment is\u003cspan\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003cem\u003enot\u003c/em\u003e\u003cspan\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003egraded and the scores will not be shared with anyone except your instructor and other Flatiron staff.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSelect the best answers\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"g5ba52c13c73865fd7f446f65b75b1586"}]},{"id":44912,"name":"Tools","status":"completed","unlockDate":null,"prereqs":[],"requirement":"all","sequential":true,"exportId":"g827bbea3eed131c7b50a573c55c13abb","items":[{"id":433530,"title":"Introduction to Tools","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProduct Designers, UX Designers, and UI Designers use a variety of tools.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn the last year, more companies have allowed employees to work from home. This has created a need for design and prototyping tools with better collaboration support. For this course, we consult the most current version of the \u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://uxtools.co/survey-2020\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eUX Tools Survey\u003c/a\u003e. The survey includes insights from over 4000 design practitioners from around the world to see how industry tools change from year to year. You can read through the survey to identify other tools to experiment within your design practice, but this course has elected to primarily use Figma, Invision, and Webflow as the foundations for production work in all phases.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThese tools are robust and serve the needs of UX and UI professionals to create low-fidelity mockups, high-fidelity mockups, and clickable prototypes for testing. In this prework course, we will get you set up with these tools and give you a brief walkthrough of the core features you'll need for Design Labs. We will not take a deep dive into all the features of these tools in the prework. Your instructors in the main coursework will walk you through special case scenarios and additional features to speed up workflows.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eContinue on to get set up with Figma and practice some basic layout and prototyping features.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"introduction-to-tools"},{"id":433531,"title":"Figma","type":"ContextModuleSubHeader","indent":0,"locked":false},{"id":433532,"title":"Setting Up Your Figma Account \u0026 Walkthrough","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Br1caumhZts\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we get started with Figma by creating an account, touring the interface, and learning the basics of the Figma document window.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"setting-up-your-figma-account-and-walkthrough"},{"id":433533,"title":"Birds! Design and Prototyping with Figma","type":"ContextModuleSubHeader","indent":0,"locked":false},{"id":433534,"title":"Birds: Design and Layout Introduction","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Zg6r9wZ9-rs\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we introduce the first design and prototype we'll create in the prework. This project is all about birds! Sort of. The purpose of this project is to provide a simple and manageable project that helps you to practice the basic skills of creating elements, configuring those elements, oranizing Figma files, and creating prototypes.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe link below contains all of the bird images, images of the mockups for your reference, and a completed Figma file of the resulting design. If you get \u003cem\u003ereally\u003c/em\u003e stuck, import the \u003cem\u003e'Test Project.fig'\u003c/em\u003e from the dashboard and open it up. You'll find a completed Figma file with the designs and a working prototype.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca id=\"1989981\" class=\"instructure_file_link inline_disabled\" href=\"viewer/files/Figma%20-%20Design%20and%20Prototyping.zip?canvas_=1\u0026amp;canvas_qs_wrap=1\" target=\"_blank\" data-api-endpoint=\"https://learning.flatironschool.com/api/v1/courses/4832/files/1989981\" data-api-returntype=\"File\"\u003eFigma - Design and Prototyping.zip\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"birds-design-and-layout-introduction"},{"id":433535,"title":"Birds: Design and Layout","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003ciframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/3p8JQ5rukTI\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen=\"\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we will walk through the creation of two layouts about birds. The content is silly and simplistic, but that's good since we're just getting started with Figma and there are many features to explore. The project is designed to be straightforward and attainable, but if you get stuck, feel free to pause the video or run through the process more than once until you've recreated the designs in the video.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"birds-design-and-layout"},{"id":433536,"title":"Birds: Prototyping","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/irjN-HzcQ0k\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eIn this video, we wrap up our first dive into Figma by connecting the two bird layouts to create a prototype that transitions similarly to a native iPhone app. We discuss the configuration of prototype features and some of the benefits of clickable prototypes.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"birds-prototyping"},{"id":433537,"title":"Flowershop: Additional Layout and Prototyping Practice","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003ch3\u003eWelcome to the Flowershop\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e**This is optional**\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn the download file, you will find another design to construct in Figma and create a Prototype from. Open up the Figma file to inspect the fonts used and to understand how the linking works between the pages. This design is slightly more involved but doesn't use any new ideas or features except the ellipse tool (located in the same spot as the rectangle tool).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca id=\"1990521\" class=\"instructure_file_link inline_disabled\" href=\"viewer/files/Flowers%20-%20Design%20and%20Prototyping.zip?canvas_=1\u0026amp;canvas_qs_wrap=1\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eFlowers - Design and Prototyping.zip\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"flowershop-additional-layout-and-prototyping-practice"},{"id":433538,"title":"Additional Practice with Figma","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003ch2\u003eFigma\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWatch the videos \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLXDU_eVOJTx6zk5MDarIs0asNoZqlRG23\"\u003ein this playlist\u003c/a\u003e, created by Figma, to continue to level up your skills!\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eFigjam\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn addition to Figma, you'll use Figjam for some of the workshops. FigJam is a collaborative, virtual whiteboard. It's useful for brainstorming, organizing ideas, diagramming, and group critique session. Watch the video below to see how Figma's design team uses it.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/FxdoM1B7Wo8\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"additional-practice-with-figma"},{"id":433539,"title":"Invision","type":"ContextModuleSubHeader","indent":0,"locked":false},{"id":433540,"title":"Setting Up Your Invision Account \u0026 Walkthrough","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/_KdmrSi_2q0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eIn this video, we create an account for the Invision app. We also tour the app and create a prototype using our two bird layouts.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"setting-up-your-invision-account-and-walkthrough"},{"id":433541,"title":"Webflow","type":"ContextModuleSubHeader","indent":0,"locked":false},{"id":433542,"title":"Set Up Your Webflow Account and Webflow 101","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cimg role=\"presentation\" src=\"https://miro.medium.com/max/2000/1*1xAAAI2aD5lo__MzqxutLw.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"448\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWe've partnered with Webflow to teach you web design and to help you craft a professional product design portfolio of your work at Flatiron. You'll also get a free year of CMS hosting for your custom portfolio site.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eStep 1\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eApply for a student account and discount at \u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://webflow.com/for/classroom\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eWebflow\u003c/a\u003e. It can take a few business days to hear back from them.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eStep 2\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCheck out what Webflow can do by \u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://webflow.com/websites/portfolio\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ebrowsing some of the portfolio's\u003c/a\u003e people have created with Webflow.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eStep 3\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eComplete the \u003ca href=\"https://university.webflow.com/courses/webflow-101-crash-course\"\u003eWebflow 101: Crash Course\u003c/a\u003e (2hrs) before your first day at Flatiron.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIf you want to go even deeper with Webflow you can complete the \u003ca href=\"https://university.webflow.com/courses/ultimate-web-design-course\"\u003eUltimate Web Design Course\u003c/a\u003e (5hrs).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","exportId":"set-up-your-webflow-account-and-webflow-101"}]},{"id":44913,"name":"Understanding Product Design","status":"completed","unlockDate":null,"prereqs":[],"requirement":"all","sequential":true,"exportId":"g57401be663fff17bcc96e3759a1d4d6a","items":[{"id":433543,"title":"What is Product Design?","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/nzwGkBMZuGM\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDistinguishing Product Design from UX Design can be difficult since the skills and processes they employ are similar. However, when considering the entire life cycle of a product, the true nature of the Product Designer is revealed. In this video, we talk about the considerations and context of Product Design, UX Design, and UI Design to clarify how we define the terms and the roles these designers play in the creation of new products and the maintenance of existing products.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"what-is-product-design"},{"id":433544,"title":"Product Design and McDonalds","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/g0pKFInBOsA\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe McDonald Brothers innovated the restaurant business with SpeeDee system. It allowed them to create a consistent product much faster than their competition and changed the nature of food service forever. In this video, we discuss the methods that the McDonald brothers used to create their system and how those practices align with Product Design.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"product-design-and-mcdonalds"},{"id":433545,"title":"A Note Taking App","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/_FmuA4IDEfU\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we explore the initial research and thought process that goes into conceiving a product that has a market fit. We explore the idea of creating a Note-taking app and compare the potential competing apps. We do all of this to understand how a Product Designer, UX Designer, and UI Designer could contribute to this process in different ways.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"a-note-taking-app"},{"id":433546,"title":"Design Lab: Grocery List App","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/BQoytSb0IcU\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we set up the Grocery List App Design Lab and talk through an approach to completing both parts of the assignment.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"design-lab-grocery-list-app"},{"id":433547,"title":"User Experience Design","type":"ContextModuleSubHeader","indent":0,"locked":false},{"id":433548,"title":"What is User Experience Design?","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003ciframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/AIL9iiYrFys\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen=\"\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we discuss a general UX process that is employed by UX Designers and Product Designers to uncover user needs and market potential for products.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"what-is-user-experience-design"},{"id":433549,"title":"Design Lab: Agency UX Process","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003ch3\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUX Agency Processes\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUX agencies are companies that work with brands to solve UX problems. They are experts in the UX process and serve companies that want to improve on products and create valuable user experiences.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this activity, explore three UX agency websites to investigate how they lay out their UX process. No two consultancy/agencies are exactly alike and they talk about their process in different ways. Think about what they are trying to convey with their process description and how it maps back to the three general phases of the UX process: \u003cstrong\u003eResearch\u003c/strong\u003e, \u003cstrong\u003eIdeation\u003c/strong\u003e, and \u003cstrong\u003eTesting. \u003c/strong\u003eWhile investigating the following agency process, take notes of the similarities between the process and the differences.\u003cstrong\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e** This page links to three agencies, but feel free to review agencies other than those listed here.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://www.instrument.com/what-we-do\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eInstrument\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe instrument is a design-centric firm that offers many services. Highly regarded for their work with Nike, Levi, and Pinterest.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://www.ideo.com/about\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIDEO\u003c/strong\u003e \u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://www.ideo.com/about\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e\u003c/a\u003eIDEO is a world-renowned design agency that has worked with some of the largest brands in the world. IDEO has innovated in the UX design space and has been a steadfast thought-leader for generations of designers. They are a company to watch and follow. Look for the slideshow titled \"How We Work\" to see their process\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://bakkenbaeck.com/about\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eBacken\u0026amp;Baeck\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBacken\u0026amp;Baeck is an international Product Design company that takes a creative and informed approach to innovate products that are both practical and elegant\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTo complete this design lab, you should:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e1. Investigate three agency websites to read about their work and process. Take notes about the agencies in a deck or document\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e2. Compare and contrast the ways that agencies think about their UX/UI process and note the similarities and difference\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e3. Think about how the processes explained on the agency sites related to our simple models around the UX process (Research/Ideation/Testing \u0026amp; the Double Diamond Framework)\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"design-lab-agency-ux-process"},{"id":433550,"title":"User Interface Design","type":"ContextModuleSubHeader","indent":0,"locked":false},{"id":433551,"title":"What is User Interface Design?","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/LUgsKxUEzNQ\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we explore the topic of interface design and review a real-world example of how low fidelity wireframes are converted into mid-fidelity prototypes.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"what-is-user-interface-design"},{"id":433552,"title":"Examples of High Quality Interface Design","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003ciframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/MSEbXDnl420\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen=\"\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we talk about a few high-quality design projects and talk about what makes them so good. The purpose of this video is to give you some insight into professional design to help focus your study within the Flatiron Product Design course.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"examples-of-high-quality-interface-design"},{"id":433553,"title":"Emerging Markets: Product Ideas from Data and Insights","type":"ContextModuleSubHeader","indent":0,"locked":false},{"id":433554,"title":"Market Research","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/T7-IStx44ns\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we review the market research for industrializing rural communities. We talk through the intent of the project and specify the requirements for the project.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"market-research"},{"id":433555,"title":"Design Lab: Product Concepts for Developing Markets","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003ch3\u003eProject Outline\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis project requires you to review market research related to food production in emerging markets. The paper does an excellent job of conveying the circumstances of farmers and households in rural communities and the troubles they face around industrialization. The goal of the research is to help improve the lives of farmers and the communities they serve. Your job is to read through the research and findings and create product concepts that will help farmers and producers navigate a changing economy. This project may include additional research on your part.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDownload the market research here:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca id=\"1993572\" class=\"instructure_file_link instructure_scribd_file inline_disabled\" href=\"viewer/files/Marketing%20Research%20for%20Food%20Products%20in%20Developing%20Countries%20-%20IDL-9543.pdf?canvas_=1\u0026amp;canvas_qs_wrap=1\" target=\"_blank\" data-canvas-previewable=\"true\"\u003eMarketing Research for Food Products in Developing Countries - IDL-9543.pdf\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eThings to consider\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThis research paper is from the 1980s and doesn't talk about modern technology like smartphones and the internet. For the purposes of this project, you should \u003cem\u003epretend\u003c/em\u003e that the paper discussed modern-day emerging markets that have modern technology like computers and smartphones. Your product ideas should be software solutions, not industrial solutions. In the video, I laid out some possible product ideas that you might consider. You are free to use those ideas or to develop your own.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThis is your first time jumping into the Product Design process. I know that it can be intimidating to be asked to create solutions to complex problems. Remember, this is mostly a thought exercise. \u003cstrong\u003eThere are no wrong answers!\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003eYou should try your best to be creative and to look for problems that resonate with you in the case studies.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTry to develop two completely different solutions to different problems. For instance, if your first problem solves the issue of access to credit, your second solution should solve a different problem.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThis project is intentionally open-ended. You are not required to follow any best practices in terms of processes or deliverables. You are free to work with a pen and paper, or with Google docs, or with any other documentation method that is accessible to you.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHave fun! This is your first dive into an incredible career, so make the most of it\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eProject Requirements\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRead through the research of food production in emerging markets\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/strong\u003eMake sure you read through part one of the paper because it represents the bulk of the overall research and outlines the diagrams of traditional agricultural economies and the emerging economies that include industrialization. The problems studied are outlined in part one as well as methodology. It's a good example of excellent research.\u003cbr\u003eAlso, be sure to find case studies that resonate with and inspire you to find solutions.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIdentify problems to solve\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/strong\u003eAfter you've read through the research, document the problems that you want to solve. You don't have to be extremely specific, but you should indicate three things: The cause of the problems, the persons impacted by the problem, and any existing solutions to the problem\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIdeate possible solutions to the problems\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/strong\u003eTry not to be critical of your ideas. It can be hard to trust your instincts. List out as many ideas as you can think of. Think about what technologies you could use (Phones, tablets, computers) and how you would implement a solution. Who else would be involved? What would it cost? What kind of training would the rural populations require? Be creative. The sky is the limit, but be sure to indicate solutions to both problems.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReduce your list of ideas to just the best solutions\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr\u003eEven if you developed a hundred ideas in step 3, you can only implement one solution for each problem. Now is the time to be critical and cut out ideas that are impractical or might require more effort than they are worth. Find the best solution to each of your problems and start a document for each problem that explains why your solution makes sense.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCreate a project plan\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/strong\u003eIn the final step of this process, you will elaborate on each of your problem docs to indicate all of the considerations of a Product Designer. The following list isn't intended to be exhaustive. Try to think about all of the hurdles that you might face while developing your product.\u003cbr\u003eConsider the following questions:\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat further research is needed?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat kind of prototype might make sense?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eShould you consult with other specialists?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHow will you conduct testing?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat other hurdles might there be to success?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOnce the product is launched, how will you maintain it?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eKeep your product ideas. After you've completed the Flatiron Product Design program, you can look back at this project and reevaluate your choices. It will be a good indicator of how far you've come in just a few months.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eGood Luck!\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"design-lab-product-concepts-for-developing-markets"},{"id":433556,"title":"Design Critique","type":"ContextModuleSubHeader","indent":0,"locked":false},{"id":433557,"title":"The Role of Critique in Learning","type":"WikiPage","indent":1,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003cp\u003eThe fastest way to improve as a designer is to present your work to others and invite criticism. This can be an emotional exercise for new designers. We will encourage you to be bold and present your work, early and often, in this program. During the program, you will need to practice communicating your design work, whether verbally or through reports and presentations. You will not only be able to level up faster, but you will also stand out as a candidate during job interviews.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou can prepare for this by reading, \u003ca href=\"https://www.aiga.org/resources/how-to-survive-a-critique-a-guide-to-giving-and-receiving-feedback\"\u003eHow to Survive a Critique: A Guide to Giving and Receiving Feedback\u003c/a\u003e, by AIGA.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eYou'll also provide feedback on others' design work\u003c/span\u003e To help you build this skill, read \u003ca href=\"https://alistapart.com/article/async-design-critique-giving-feedback/\"\u003eAsynchronous Design Critique: Giving Feedback\u003c/a\u003e, by A List Apart.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eFinally, watch Julia Kestner's presentation on how her team turned a bad critique experience into \"everyone's happy place.\"\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/-FGRueop8TE\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAnd if you want to see how a product design team approaches a critique session, watch Figma's live critique session.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/nu1yQay27pM\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"the-role-of-critique-in-learning"}]},{"id":44914,"name":"Post-assessment","status":"completed","unlockDate":null,"prereqs":[],"requirement":"all","sequential":false,"exportId":"g1a4bd64c327f30caf3a6496bd4f40c4b","items":[{"id":433558,"title":"Prework: Post-Assessment","type":"Quizzes::Quiz","indent":0,"locked":false,"assignmentExportId":"gd12f81ce434304bcaa1629aac564defe","questionCount":10,"timeLimit":null,"attempts":3,"graded":true,"pointsPossible":10.0,"dueAt":null,"lockAt":null,"unlockAt":null,"requirement":"must_submit","completed":true,"content":"\u003ch3\u003eIntroduction\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCongratulations on making it through all the pre-work lessons! You should be proud of the effort you put in to get to this point. Your final step is passing our post test aAssessment - a 10 question multiple choice quiz designed to assess what you've learned from pre-work.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCompleting this assessment is mandatory to start in class - you'll have \u003cstrong\u003e3 attempts\u003c/strong\u003e to pass the assessment with a score of \u003cstrong\u003e80% or higher\u003c/strong\u003e by your \u003cstrong\u003eenrollment deadline\u003c/strong\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eTiming\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis is not a timed test, but it is intended to be taken in one sitting. We don't guarantee that Canvas will keep track of your progress if, for example, you leave the quiz open overnight. If you find that you don't pass the first time - do not be discouraged! - you'll be able to see your score and review the topics you missed before attempting again.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eAcademic Honesty\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis multiple-choice assessment is open book but should be completed individually, without assistance. The goal is ensuring that we have an accurate assessment of your ability to use the concepts and techniques covered in the pre-work.\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"g39ff64daa7bf95da48e00f33dd802cc8"}]},{"id":44915,"name":"Next Steps","status":"completed","unlockDate":null,"prereqs":[],"requirement":"all","sequential":false,"exportId":"gb4611cdfb9cc856071fc4f5bb3d9c552","items":[{"id":433559,"title":"Next Steps","type":"WikiPage","indent":0,"locked":false,"requirement":"must_view","completed":true,"content":"\u003ch3\u003eCongratulations!\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou have completed the prework for Product Design. We encourage you to continue playing with Figma and Invision to hone your skills with those two tools. We also encourage you to engage with admissions if you have any questions about the activities in prework. Remember this is just the first step in a lifelong journey of discovery and creativity. We can't wait to see you in the classroom. :)\u003c/p\u003e","exportId":"next-steps"}]}],"pages":[{"exportId":"starting-your-journey","title":"Starting Your Journey","type":"WikiPage","content":"","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"setting-up-your-invision-account-and-walkthrough","title":"Setting Up Your Invision Account \u0026 Walkthrough","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/_KdmrSi_2q0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eIn this video, we create an account for the Invision app. We also tour the app and create a prototype using our two bird layouts.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"navigating-canvas","title":"Navigating Canvas","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/PVfkFD45hL0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDashboard\u003c/strong\u003e - the first thing you see when you log into Canvas, the Dashboard gives a high level view of the courses in which you're enrolled. Your instructor will release new courses as you go through the program.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eGlobal Navigation\u003c/strong\u003e - static menu on the left side of the page and accessible from any page on Canvas, the Global Navigation gives you direct access to your courses and other information in Canvas.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSidebar\u003c/strong\u003e - found within each course, the Sidebar houses various features that allow access to the course materials.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eView the video tutorial for more information on how to use Canvas effectively.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"market-research","title":"Market Research","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/T7-IStx44ns\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we review the market research for industrializing rural communities. We talk through the intent of the project and specify the requirements for the project.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"product-design-and-mcdonalds","title":"Product Design and McDonalds","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/g0pKFInBOsA\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe McDonald Brothers innovated the restaurant business with SpeeDee system. It allowed them to create a consistent product much faster than their competition and changed the nature of food service forever. In this video, we discuss the methods that the McDonald brothers used to create their system and how those practices align with Product Design.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"additional-practice-with-figma","title":"Additional Practice with Figma","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003ch2\u003eFigma\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWatch the videos \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLXDU_eVOJTx6zk5MDarIs0asNoZqlRG23\"\u003ein this playlist\u003c/a\u003e, created by Figma, to continue to level up your skills!\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eFigjam\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn addition to Figma, you'll use Figjam for some of the workshops. FigJam is a collaborative, virtual whiteboard. It's useful for brainstorming, organizing ideas, diagramming, and group critique session. Watch the video below to see how Figma's design team uses it.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/FxdoM1B7Wo8\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"flowershop-additional-layout-and-prototyping-practice","title":"Flowershop: Additional Layout and Prototyping Practice","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003ch3\u003eWelcome to the Flowershop\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e**This is optional**\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn the download file, you will find another design to construct in Figma and create a Prototype from. Open up the Figma file to inspect the fonts used and to understand how the linking works between the pages. This design is slightly more involved but doesn't use any new ideas or features except the ellipse tool (located in the same spot as the rectangle tool).\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca id=\"1990521\" class=\"instructure_file_link inline_disabled\" href=\"viewer/files/Flowers%20-%20Design%20and%20Prototyping.zip?canvas_=1\u0026amp;canvas_qs_wrap=1\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eFlowers - Design and Prototyping.zip\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"examples-of-high-quality-interface-design","title":"Examples of High Quality Interface Design","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003ciframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/MSEbXDnl420\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen=\"\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we talk about a few high-quality design projects and talk about what makes them so good. The purpose of this video is to give you some insight into professional design to help focus your study within the Flatiron Product Design course.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"welcome","title":"Welcome!","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003ch4\u003eWelcome to Flatiron School! We're thrilled that you've joined our community of learners!\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe following content is designed for passionate, curious, self-driven, and serious about learning. We are comrades in a never-ending quest for knowledge. While there are no shortcuts, we believe that you will learn quickly by providing knowledge in an optimized order, reinforcing knowledge with hands-on, feedback-driven practice, and providing space for discussion.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOur goal is to provide the right materials, support, and structure \u003cem\u003eyou\u003c/em\u003e need to discover your own love for designing outstanding products.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePre-work is required to start at Flatiron School\u003c/strong\u003e and you have access to this useful material even prior to applying. Please note some resources mentioned throughout are only available to enrolled students, such as community and technical coach support.\u0026nbsp;\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIf youâ€™re just researching the programs, keep in mind that this is the same pre-course work admitted students are working through. Some of this information will seem granular, just work through as much as you can and know that you will have time to revisit content should you go through our admissions process. \u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch4\u003eThe Flatiron Community\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWe don't believe in learning alone. As you make progress, expect to bump into other learners just like you, ready and willing to help each other succeed. Together, we can go further than we could ever go alone. We expect everyone here to be friendly, respectful, helpful, and nice.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"what-is-user-experience-design","title":"What is User Experience Design?","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003ciframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/AIL9iiYrFys\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen=\"\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we discuss a general UX process that is employed by UX Designers and Product Designers to uncover user needs and market potential for products.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"birds-prototyping","title":"Birds: Prototyping","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/irjN-HzcQ0k\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eIn this video, we wrap up our first dive into Figma by connecting the two bird layouts to create a prototype that transitions similarly to a native iPhone app. We discuss the configuration of prototype features and some of the benefits of clickable prototypes.\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"what-is-product-design","title":"What is Product Design?","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/nzwGkBMZuGM\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDistinguishing Product Design from UX Design can be difficult since the skills and processes they employ are similar. However, when considering the entire life cycle of a product, the true nature of the Product Designer is revealed. In this video, we talk about the considerations and context of Product Design, UX Design, and UI Design to clarify how we define the terms and the roles these designers play in the creation of new products and the maintenance of existing products.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"design-lab-grocery-list-app","title":"Design Lab: Grocery List App","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/BQoytSb0IcU\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we set up the Grocery List App Design Lab and talk through an approach to completing both parts of the assignment.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"setting-up-your-figma-account-and-walkthrough","title":"Setting Up Your Figma Account \u0026 Walkthrough","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Br1caumhZts\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we get started with Figma by creating an account, touring the interface, and learning the basics of the Figma document window.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"design-lab-product-concepts-for-developing-markets","title":"Design Lab: Product Concepts for Developing Markets","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003ch3\u003eProject Outline\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis project requires you to review market research related to food production in emerging markets. The paper does an excellent job of conveying the circumstances of farmers and households in rural communities and the troubles they face around industrialization. The goal of the research is to help improve the lives of farmers and the communities they serve. Your job is to read through the research and findings and create product concepts that will help farmers and producers navigate a changing economy. This project may include additional research on your part.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDownload the market research here:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca id=\"1993572\" class=\"instructure_file_link instructure_scribd_file inline_disabled\" href=\"viewer/files/Marketing%20Research%20for%20Food%20Products%20in%20Developing%20Countries%20-%20IDL-9543.pdf?canvas_=1\u0026amp;canvas_qs_wrap=1\" target=\"_blank\" data-canvas-previewable=\"true\"\u003eMarketing Research for Food Products in Developing Countries - IDL-9543.pdf\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eThings to consider\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThis research paper is from the 1980s and doesn't talk about modern technology like smartphones and the internet. For the purposes of this project, you should \u003cem\u003epretend\u003c/em\u003e that the paper discussed modern-day emerging markets that have modern technology like computers and smartphones. Your product ideas should be software solutions, not industrial solutions. In the video, I laid out some possible product ideas that you might consider. You are free to use those ideas or to develop your own.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThis is your first time jumping into the Product Design process. I know that it can be intimidating to be asked to create solutions to complex problems. Remember, this is mostly a thought exercise. \u003cstrong\u003eThere are no wrong answers!\u0026nbsp;\u003c/strong\u003eYou should try your best to be creative and to look for problems that resonate with you in the case studies.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eTry to develop two completely different solutions to different problems. For instance, if your first problem solves the issue of access to credit, your second solution should solve a different problem.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eThis project is intentionally open-ended. You are not required to follow any best practices in terms of processes or deliverables. You are free to work with a pen and paper, or with Google docs, or with any other documentation method that is accessible to you.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHave fun! This is your first dive into an incredible career, so make the most of it\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eProject Requirements\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eRead through the research of food production in emerging markets\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/strong\u003eMake sure you read through part one of the paper because it represents the bulk of the overall research and outlines the diagrams of traditional agricultural economies and the emerging economies that include industrialization. The problems studied are outlined in part one as well as methodology. It's a good example of excellent research.\u003cbr\u003eAlso, be sure to find case studies that resonate with and inspire you to find solutions.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIdentify problems to solve\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/strong\u003eAfter you've read through the research, document the problems that you want to solve. You don't have to be extremely specific, but you should indicate three things: The cause of the problems, the persons impacted by the problem, and any existing solutions to the problem\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIdeate possible solutions to the problems\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/strong\u003eTry not to be critical of your ideas. It can be hard to trust your instincts. List out as many ideas as you can think of. Think about what technologies you could use (Phones, tablets, computers) and how you would implement a solution. Who else would be involved? What would it cost? What kind of training would the rural populations require? Be creative. The sky is the limit, but be sure to indicate solutions to both problems.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReduce your list of ideas to just the best solutions\u003c/strong\u003e\u003cbr\u003eEven if you developed a hundred ideas in step 3, you can only implement one solution for each problem. Now is the time to be critical and cut out ideas that are impractical or might require more effort than they are worth. Find the best solution to each of your problems and start a document for each problem that explains why your solution makes sense.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eCreate a project plan\u003cbr\u003e\u003c/strong\u003eIn the final step of this process, you will elaborate on each of your problem docs to indicate all of the considerations of a Product Designer. The following list isn't intended to be exhaustive. Try to think about all of the hurdles that you might face while developing your product.\u003cbr\u003eConsider the following questions:\n\u003col\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat further research is needed?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat kind of prototype might make sense?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eShould you consult with other specialists?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eHow will you conduct testing?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eWhat other hurdles might there be to success?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eOnce the product is launched, how will you maintain it?\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eKeep your product ideas. After you've completed the Flatiron Product Design program, you can look back at this project and reevaluate your choices. It will be a good indicator of how far you've come in just a few months.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eGood Luck!\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"what-is-canvas","title":"What is Canvas?","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003eCanvas is a learning platform used by universities and educational institutions across the country and the world. Flatiron School uses Canvas to deliver all curriculum content for your program.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCanvas is where all official Flatiron School communication, assignment submission, grading, attendance, etc., will take place for the entirety of your course. You should check Canvas multiple times a day for updates, announcements, assignments, and the day's schedule. Canvas hosts many features that you will become familiar with over your time with Flatiron School. The following lessons will introduce you to and explain some of these most important functions. You can also download the Canvas app from the App Store.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"next-steps","title":"Next Steps","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003ch3\u003eCongratulations!\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou have completed the prework for Product Design. We encourage you to continue playing with Figma and Invision to hone your skills with those two tools. We also encourage you to engage with admissions if you have any questions about the activities in prework. Remember this is just the first step in a lifelong journey of discovery and creativity. We can't wait to see you in the classroom. :)\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"what-is-user-interface-design","title":"What is User Interface Design?","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/LUgsKxUEzNQ\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we explore the topic of interface design and review a real-world example of how low fidelity wireframes are converted into mid-fidelity prototypes.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"birds-design-and-layout","title":"Birds: Design and Layout","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003ciframe width=\"560\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/3p8JQ5rukTI\" title=\"YouTube video player\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen=\"\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we will walk through the creation of two layouts about birds. The content is silly and simplistic, but that's good since we're just getting started with Figma and there are many features to explore. The project is designed to be straightforward and attainable, but if you get stuck, feel free to pause the video or run through the process more than once until you've recreated the designs in the video.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"a-note-taking-app","title":"A Note Taking App","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/_FmuA4IDEfU\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we explore the initial research and thought process that goes into conceiving a product that has a market fit. We explore the idea of creating a Note-taking app and compare the potential competing apps. We do all of this to understand how a Product Designer, UX Designer, and UI Designer could contribute to this process in different ways.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"design-lab-agency-ux-process","title":"Design Lab: Agency UX Process","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003ch3\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eUX Agency Processes\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUX agencies are companies that work with brands to solve UX problems. They are experts in the UX process and serve companies that want to improve on products and create valuable user experiences.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this activity, explore three UX agency websites to investigate how they lay out their UX process. No two consultancy/agencies are exactly alike and they talk about their process in different ways. Think about what they are trying to convey with their process description and how it maps back to the three general phases of the UX process: \u003cstrong\u003eResearch\u003c/strong\u003e, \u003cstrong\u003eIdeation\u003c/strong\u003e, and \u003cstrong\u003eTesting. \u003c/strong\u003eWhile investigating the following agency process, take notes of the similarities between the process and the differences.\u003cstrong\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cem\u003e** This page links to three agencies, but feel free to review agencies other than those listed here.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/em\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://www.instrument.com/what-we-do\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eInstrument\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe instrument is a design-centric firm that offers many services. Highly regarded for their work with Nike, Levi, and Pinterest.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://www.ideo.com/about\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eIDEO\u003c/strong\u003e \u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://www.ideo.com/about\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e\u003c/a\u003eIDEO is a world-renowned design agency that has worked with some of the largest brands in the world. IDEO has innovated in the UX design space and has been a steadfast thought-leader for generations of designers. They are a company to watch and follow. Look for the slideshow titled \"How We Work\" to see their process\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://bakkenbaeck.com/about\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eBacken\u0026amp;Baeck\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBacken\u0026amp;Baeck is an international Product Design company that takes a creative and informed approach to innovate products that are both practical and elegant\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTo complete this design lab, you should:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e1. Investigate three agency websites to read about their work and process. Take notes about the agencies in a deck or document\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e2. Compare and contrast the ways that agencies think about their UX/UI process and note the similarities and difference\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e3. Think about how the processes explained on the agency sites related to our simple models around the UX process (Research/Ideation/Testing \u0026amp; the Double Diamond Framework)\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"product-design-program-overview","title":"Product Design Program Overview","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/A4c4uSOE7Ic\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we discuss the overall course structure for the Product Design program and talk about all five phases of the program in detail.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"set-up-your-webflow-account-and-webflow-101","title":"Set Up Your Webflow Account and Webflow 101","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cimg role=\"presentation\" src=\"https://miro.medium.com/max/2000/1*1xAAAI2aD5lo__MzqxutLw.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"448\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWe've partnered with Webflow to teach you web design and to help you craft a professional product design portfolio of your work at Flatiron. You'll also get a free year of CMS hosting for your custom portfolio site.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eStep 1\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eApply for a student account and discount at \u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://webflow.com/for/classroom\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eWebflow\u003c/a\u003e. It can take a few business days to hear back from them.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eStep 2\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCheck out what Webflow can do by \u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://webflow.com/websites/portfolio\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ebrowsing some of the portfolio's\u003c/a\u003e people have created with Webflow.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eStep 3\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eComplete the \u003ca href=\"https://university.webflow.com/courses/webflow-101-crash-course\"\u003eWebflow 101: Crash Course\u003c/a\u003e (2hrs) before your first day at Flatiron.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003eIf you want to go even deeper with Webflow you can complete the \u003ca href=\"https://university.webflow.com/courses/ultimate-web-design-course\"\u003eUltimate Web Design Course\u003c/a\u003e (5hrs).\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"lesson-types-in-canvas","title":"Lesson Types in Canvas","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003ch2\u003eCOURSES\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYour Flatiron School program is broken up into courses. Each course represents a section of our core curriculum. The Flatiron School course structure is something that we'll discuss in more detail in later lessons. For now, we'll discuss the content types you are likely to see in the Canvas platform.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eMODULES\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFlatiron School organizes content within courses by breaking them up into modules. The modules will control the entire course flow, and within them, you'll find all your lessons, labs, assignments, and quizzes for the course. Modules can hold several types of content:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePage:\u003c/strong\u003e a page of content to read\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDiscussion:\u003c/strong\u003e a course discussion in which teachers and students can actively participate\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eQuiz:\u003c/strong\u003e A course quiz, generally multiple choice questions or true/false questions\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eAssignment:\u003c/strong\u003e A course assignment. Assignments are graded projects that count toward your final score\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eLink or External Tool:\u003c/strong\u003e an external link or tool to view information outside of the course\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFile:\u003c/strong\u003e a file to download or view\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou may be required to perform certain actions to complete a module. Requirements may include:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eView:\u003c/strong\u003e You must view the item.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eMark as done:\u003c/strong\u003e You must mark the module item as done before progressing to the next item.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eContribute:\u003c/strong\u003e You must post a reply to the discussion topic or contribute content to a page.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSubmit:\u003c/strong\u003e You must submit the assignment, graded discussion, or quiz.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eScore at least X points:\u003c/strong\u003e You must submit the assignment with a minimum of the shown score.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou can find the 'Modules' button on the sidebar on the left-hand side within each course.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch2\u003eASSIGNMENTS\u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhile the module controls the flow of the entire course, you can also access a running list of your course assignments via the 'Assignments' button on your Sidebar on the left-hand side within the course.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eBy default, assignments are grouped by overdue assignments, upcoming assignments, undated assignments, and past assignments.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eEach assignment includes an icon designating an assignment, discussion, or quiz and will also display availability dates, due dates, and the number of points the assignment is worth.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou can find the 'Assignments' button on the sidebar on the left-hand side within each course.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"birds-design-and-layout-introduction","title":"Birds: Design and Layout Introduction","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Zg6r9wZ9-rs\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this video, we introduce the first design and prototype we'll create in the prework. This project is all about birds! Sort of. The purpose of this project is to provide a simple and manageable project that helps you to practice the basic skills of creating elements, configuring those elements, oranizing Figma files, and creating prototypes.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe link below contains all of the bird images, images of the mockups for your reference, and a completed Figma file of the resulting design. If you get \u003cem\u003ereally\u003c/em\u003e stuck, import the \u003cem\u003e'Test Project.fig'\u003c/em\u003e from the dashboard and open it up. You'll find a completed Figma file with the designs and a working prototype.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca id=\"1989981\" class=\"instructure_file_link inline_disabled\" href=\"viewer/files/Figma%20-%20Design%20and%20Prototyping.zip?canvas_=1\u0026amp;canvas_qs_wrap=1\" target=\"_blank\" data-api-endpoint=\"https://learning.flatironschool.com/api/v1/courses/4832/files/1989981\" data-api-returntype=\"File\"\u003eFigma - Design and Prototyping.zip\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"introduction-to-tools","title":"Introduction to Tools","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eProduct Designers, UX Designers, and UI Designers use a variety of tools.\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn the last year, more companies have allowed employees to work from home. This has created a need for design and prototyping tools with better collaboration support. For this course, we consult the most current version of the \u003ca class=\"inline_disabled\" href=\"https://uxtools.co/survey-2020\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eUX Tools Survey\u003c/a\u003e. The survey includes insights from over 4000 design practitioners from around the world to see how industry tools change from year to year. You can read through the survey to identify other tools to experiment within your design practice, but this course has elected to primarily use Figma, Invision, and Webflow as the foundations for production work in all phases.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThese tools are robust and serve the needs of UX and UI professionals to create low-fidelity mockups, high-fidelity mockups, and clickable prototypes for testing. In this prework course, we will get you set up with these tools and give you a brief walkthrough of the core features you'll need for Design Labs. We will not take a deep dive into all the features of these tools in the prework. Your instructors in the main coursework will walk you through special case scenarios and additional features to speed up workflows.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eContinue on to get set up with Figma and practice some basic layout and prototyping features.\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false},{"exportId":"the-role-of-critique-in-learning","title":"The Role of Critique in Learning","type":"WikiPage","content":"\u003cp\u003eThe fastest way to improve as a designer is to present your work to others and invite criticism. This can be an emotional exercise for new designers. We will encourage you to be bold and present your work, early and often, in this program. During the program, you will need to practice communicating your design work, whether verbally or through reports and presentations. You will not only be able to level up faster, but you will also stand out as a candidate during job interviews.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eYou can prepare for this by reading, \u003ca href=\"https://www.aiga.org/resources/how-to-survive-a-critique-a-guide-to-giving-and-receiving-feedback\"\u003eHow to Survive a Critique: A Guide to Giving and Receiving Feedback\u003c/a\u003e, by AIGA.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eYou'll also provide feedback on others' design work\u003c/span\u003e To help you build this skill, read \u003ca href=\"https://alistapart.com/article/async-design-critique-giving-feedback/\"\u003eAsynchronous Design Critique: Giving Feedback\u003c/a\u003e, by A List Apart.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan\u003eFinally, watch Julia Kestner's presentation on how her team turned a bad critique experience into \"everyone's happy place.\"\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/-FGRueop8TE\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAnd if you want to see how a product design team approaches a critique session, watch Figma's live critique session.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ciframe title=\"YouTube video player\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/nu1yQay27pM\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\"\u003e\u003c/iframe\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e","frontPage":false}],"assignments":[],"discussion_topics":[],"quizzes":[{"exportId":"g39ff64daa7bf95da48e00f33dd802cc8","title":"Prework: Post-Assessment","type":"Quizzes::Quiz","content":"\u003ch3\u003eIntroduction\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCongratulations on making it through all the pre-work lessons! You should be proud of the effort you put in to get to this point. Your final step is passing our post test aAssessment - a 10 question multiple choice quiz designed to assess what you've learned from pre-work.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eCompleting this assessment is mandatory to start in class - you'll have \u003cstrong\u003e3 attempts\u003c/strong\u003e to pass the assessment with a score of \u003cstrong\u003e80% or higher\u003c/strong\u003e by your \u003cstrong\u003eenrollment deadline\u003c/strong\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eTiming\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis is not a timed test, but it is intended to be taken in one sitting. We don't guarantee that Canvas will keep track of your progress if, for example, you leave the quiz open overnight. If you find that you don't pass the first time - do not be discouraged! - you'll be able to see your score and review the topics you missed before attempting again.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eAcademic Honesty\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis multiple-choice assessment is open book but should be completed individually, without assistance. The goal is ensuring that we have an accurate assessment of your ability to use the concepts and techniques covered in the pre-work.\u003c/p\u003e","assignmentExportId":"gd12f81ce434304bcaa1629aac564defe","questionCount":10,"timeLimit":null,"attempts":3,"graded":true,"pointsPossible":10.0,"dueAt":null,"lockAt":null,"unlockAt":null},{"exportId":"g5ba52c13c73865fd7f446f65b75b1586","title":"Prework: Pre Assessment","type":"Quizzes::Quiz","content":"\u003cp\u003eTake this assessment before you start the coursework. This quiz is intended to gauge your current understanding of Product Design topics before you start the prework. Do your best to answer the questions, but know that this assignment is\u003cspan\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003e\u003cem\u003enot\u003c/em\u003e\u003cspan\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/span\u003egraded and the scores will not be shared with anyone except your instructor and other Flatiron staff.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSelect the best answers\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e","assignmentExportId":"gd41d8cd98f00b204e9800998ecf8427e","questionCount":10,"timeLimit":null,"attempts":3,"graded":true,"pointsPossible":10.0,"dueAt":null,"lockAt":null,"unlockAt":null}],"files":[{"type":"folder","name":"course_image","size":null,"files":[{"type":"file","name":"PDED_card.jpg","size":75349,"files":null}]},{"type":"file","name":"Marketing Research for Food Products in Developing Countries - IDL-9543.pdf","size":5033117,"files":null},{"type":"file","name":"Figma - Design and Prototyping.zip","size":3630744,"files":null},{"type":"file","name":"Flowers - Design and Prototyping.zip","size":5525319,"files":null}]}